[{"sha":"8c0b9a21f8413fa1450421cfd73c8d47c3c2a6ec","author":{"name":"Berkin Ilbeyi","email":"5f773b6479653d0f1ae8fe9abb2a70525c143dd2@google.com"},"message":"[XLA] Avoid unnecessary evictions in while loops.

Consider the following scenario:

 a = parameter()
 ...
 w = while((a, ...)) {
   p = parameter(0)
   gte = get-tuple-element(p), index=0
   f = fusion(gte)
   ...
   ROOT root = tuple(gte, ...)
 }

Instruction 'a' is an entry computation parameter, so it has to live in the
default memory space. 'a' may be prefetched into the alternate memory for the
while use. However, the while body might be too long to keep 'a' (or 'gte') in
the alternate memory space, so an eviction would normally be necessary. This CL
introduces the concept of "parent" allocation, which refers to the allocation of
this buffer in the default memory space in the parent computation (in this case,
the parent allocation would be 'a'). In this case, we add an additional
parameter to while loop for a reference in 'a' so that evictions can be avoided.
So the output of the example with parent allocations may look like (_alt suffix
in the names indicates that the buffer lives in the alternate memory space):

 a = parameter()
 ...
 cs_alt = copy-start(a)
 ...
 cd_alt = copy-done(cs_alt)
 w = while((cd_alt, ..., a)) {
   p = parameter(0)
   gte_alt = get-tuple-element(p), index=0
   gte2 = get-tuple-element(p), index=n-1
   f = fusion(gte_alt)
   ...  # gte_alt may be freed here without an eviction.
   ...
   cs2_alt = copy-start(gte2)
   ...
   cd2_alt = copy-done(cs2_alt)
   ROOT root = tuple(cd2_alt, ..., gte2)
 }

[{"sha":"096010600d75a334c9a77a3d4cd47d84ca34ba40","author":{"name":"Kristin Laemmert","email":"30cb4a936f196f8da41f6469d07b31397d334edc@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"terraform: use hcl.MergeBodies instead of configs.MergeBodies for pro… (#29000)

* terraform: use hcl.MergeBodies instead of configs.MergeBodies for provider configuration

Previously, Terraform would return an error if the user supplied provider configuration via interactive input iff the configuration provided on the command line was missing any required attributes - even if those attributes were already set in config.

That error came from configs.MergeBody, which was designed for overriding valid configuration. It expects that the first ("base") body has all required attributes. However in the case of interactive input for provider configuration, it is perfectly valid if either or both bodies are missing required attributes, as long as the final body has all required attributes. hcl.MergeBodies works very similarly to configs.MergeBodies, with a key difference being that it only checks that all required attributes are present after the two bodies are merged.

I've updated the existing test to use interactive input vars and a schema with all required attributes. This test failed before switching from configs.MergeBodies to hcl.MergeBodies.

* add a command package test that shows that we can still have providers with dynamic configuration + required + interactive input merging

This test failed when buildProviderConfig still used configs.MergeBodies instead of hcl.MergeBodies","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/096010600d75a334c9a77a3d4cd47d84ca34ba40"}]
